Population Trends

Over the next 20 years, the U.S. Census estimates that the proportion of those over the age of 75 will grow by 92%. The graph below shows how each 10 year age demographic will change over the next 42 years.

You will notice how not only will older Americans grow as a percentage of the populations, but those between the ages of 5 and 35 will decrease as a percentage of the population

Mortality Trends

According to data provided by the USFA, those over the age of 75 are more than three times as likely to die in a fire while those between the ages of 5 and 35 are are 1/3 as likely to die in a fire.

Below you will see that although these mortality rates change overtime, their relationship with one another does not.

Putting It All Together

Using these two pieces of information, the proportion of adults over the age of 75 is growing, and the mortality rate of these older adults is higher, we can estimate the effects this will have on mortality rate.

The mortality rate was forecasted by multiplying the 2012-2016 average mortality rate for each of the age brackets by the projected population in each of those age brackets. The result confirms what we’ve already begun to observe, the mortality rate is beginning to plateau and may even rise slightly as our population becomes older.

What Can We Do?

Redefine Success

With a potential plateau of fire mortality rates coming due to an aging population, it is important to redefine what it means to be successful.

Perhaps your organization had a goal similar to:

Reduce the number of fire fatalities by 25% over the course of the next five years.

That goal could be restated to:

Reduce the fire mortality rate for each of the major age groups by 25%.

  • Children under 5
  • Children between the ages of 5 and 17
  • Adults between the ages of 18 and 35
  • Adults between the ages of 36 and 74
  • Adults over the age of 75

For smaller communities where fatalities occur infrequently other metrics can be used such as structure fire rates where property loss was greater than 50% of value or even emergency call volume where an older adult is involved.

Goal setting shouldn’t be limited to age demographics. A details analysis should be done to determine what is important for your organization.

Perhaps other important demographics for your community such as income, substance abuse, or education should be taken into consideration.

Improve Data

With these metrics getting more detailed, more and better detailed data must be collected. Your organization should consider a data quality initiative such as the one below.

Here you can ensure that meaningful data is being collected, and you can easily compare the statistics of one organization to another.

TN Data Quality Dashboard (Preview).

In addition ensure that the proper data is collected, that there is a training program for new members of your organization, and that someone is in charge of reviewing reports that are being submitted.

Resources to Affect Success

NFPA has many resources available through the program Remimber When. This program focuses on solutions such as:

  • Smoking outside.
  • Give space heaters space.
  • Smoke alarms save lives.
  • Exercise regularly.
  • Be aware of uneven surfaces.

It’s also important to establish relationships with your local organizations that can aid in reaching your older populations such as:

  • Senior Centers
  • Places of worship
  • Meals on Wheels
  • Hospitals and health clinics
  • State aging counsel or commission
  • Farmers markets
  • State consumer protection groups

These partnerships should be accompanied by clearly defined mission and goals.

Your organization could develop a home safety checklist that includes items such as:

  • Check extension cords
  • Check for trip hazards
  • Ensure there are two ways out
  • Ensure the home as smoke alarms installed.

It is important that we realize the impact this shifting demographic can have on fire mortality. We must also recognize ways that we can mitigate the effects this shift may have as well as define ways to measure success that allow us to see the progress that has been made.
